<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-04-02T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-04-02T05:00:00-05:00" n="86" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d86">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Outer Mongolia/88: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-04-02T18:00:00+08:00">April 2, 1936—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received April 2—5:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>164. Embassy’s 160, April 1, 7 p.m.<note n="32" xml:id="d86fn32">Not
                                printed.</note></p>
                        <p>Tass report of April 2 under Moscow dateline states the Mongol forces
                            repulsed the attack in the region of Tomsykbulak with heavy losses,
                            driving the Japanese-Manchurian detachments back over the border.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>